    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait i thought it was nitrogen if the bottom leaves turn yellow first? i read somewhere that nitrogen moves around the plant easily. also how do i actually check the ph without like, buying a whole lab kit? is there a cheap way to do it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right; nitrogen deficiency is often associated with older, lower leaves turning yellow first. Nitrogen is indeed mobile within the plant, which is why you see this pattern. To check the soil's pH, you can use a simple pH test kit available at garden stores or online, which are quite affordable. If you don't want to buy one, you can make a homemade pH test using vinegar and baking soda, but it's less accurate. For a quicker, rough estimate, you can also observe the color of the leaves and soil. Dark green leaves and a reddish-brown or black layer on the surface often indicate high acidity, while yellowing leaves can suggest a more alkaline soil. Remember, a pH of 6.0 to 6.8 is ideal for tomatoes. If you need to adjust the pH, you can add sulfur to lower it or lime to raise it. Just be sure to follow the instructions carefully, as changing the soil pH can affect your plants significantly.",
