    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "makes sense. i'll try the vinegar/baking soda thing. i'm just worried because it feels like the nutrients are just... vanishing. like something is eating them up before the plant can even get to them. is that actually possible for soil to just lose everything that fast?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's unlikely that nutrients are disappearing from your soil as quickly as you might think. Soil doesn't typically \"eat up\" nutrients at a rapid pace unless there's a significant issue, such as heavy compaction, which can affect water and air movement, or if there's overwatering leading to leaching. However, plants can be quite efficient at uptaking the nutrients they need, so it might just seem like they are vanishing if they are not being used efficiently. To ensure your plants are getting the right nutrients, consider conducting a soil test to determine the exact levels of available nutrients. This will help you understand if there's a deficiency or excess and how to correct it. Additionally, make sure you are applying the right type and amount of fertilizer according to the specific needs of tomato plants. If you suspect something more unusual, like pests or diseases, it's a good idea to look closely at your plants and take note of any signs that might indicate the problem. Happy gardening, and don't hesitate to reach out if you have more questions or concerns!",
